Let the matrix $\mathbf{M} = \begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix}.$
Then, we have:
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \Rightarrow \begin{pmatrix} a + 2b \\ c + 2d \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}\tag{1} \\
\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -23 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \Rightarrow \begin{pmatrix} -3a + b \\ -3c + d \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -23 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}\tag{2}
\end{align*>
Now, solving $(1)$ and $(2)$, by elimination, we get:
\begin{align*}
a + 2b & = -4 \\
-3a + b & = -23
\end{align*}
When we solve this system, we get $b = -\frac{65}{7}$ and $a = \frac{62}{7}$.
\begin{align*}
c + 2d & = 4 \\
-3c + d & = 2
\end{align*}
When we solve this system, we get $d = \frac{14}{7}$ and $c = \frac{4}{7}.$
So, the $2 \times 2$ matrix is $\mathbf{M} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{62}{7} & -\frac{65}{7} \\ \frac{4}{7} & \frac{14}{7} \end{pmatrix}.$</think>
